  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "Will I be taxed on my July 2016-January 2017 income, if I am a migrant and do my first landing to Australia in October and finally come in January?",
  "response": "Welcome to Australia! Your tax situation will depend on your residency status for tax purposes, which determines how and when you are taxed on your income.\n\n### Key Factors:\n1. **Tax Residency**:  \n   In Australia, tax residency is based on your circumstances, not just the date of your arrival. If you are considered a **tax resident**, you are taxed on your worldwide income. If you are a **non-resident**, you are taxed only on Australian-sourced income.\n\n2. **Residency Tests**:  \n   The Australian Taxation Office (ATO) uses several tests to determine residency for tax purposes. These include:\n   - The **resides test**: Whether you are living in Australia permanently or indefinitely.\n   - The **domicile test**: If your permanent home is in Australia.\n   - The **183-day test**: If you are physically present in Australia for 183 days or more in the financial year.\n   - The **superannuation test**: For government employees working overseas.\n\n3. **Timing of Income**:  \n   - **If you are a tax resident from July 2016**: You will be taxed on worldwide income from July 2016, including income earned before your arrival in October.\n   - **If you become a tax resident after your first landing in October**: You will be taxed on worldwide income from the date you become a tax resident. Income earned before that date (July 2016\u2013September 2016) may not be taxed in Australia unless it is Australian-sourced.\n   - **If you are a non-resident for the entire period**: Only Australian-sourced income will be taxed.\n\n4. **Double Taxation Agreements**:  \n   If Australia has a tax treaty with your home country, you may be able to avoid double taxation on income earned before becoming a tax resident.\n\n### Practical Steps:\n- Determine your tax residency status using the ATO\u2019s residency tests.\n- Declare all relevant income (worldwide or Australian-sourced) in your Australian tax return.\n- Seek advice from a tax professional or contact the ATO for clarification.\n\n### Example:\nIf you became a tax resident in October 2016, you would typically be taxed on worldwide income from October 2016 onwards. Income earned between July 2016 and September 2016 may not be taxed in Australia unless it is Australian-sourced.\n\nFor precise guidance, consult a tax advisor familiar with migration and residency rules.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
